{"id":14882041,"mediaExerciseId":"96fc1c69-b1d8-49a2-8aef-5ae8f41d767c","exerciseName":"3","chapterName":"25","chapterTitle":"Option Valuation","groupId":612535,"groupTitle":"Concept Questions","isPremium":true,"sectionName":"25.3","sectionTitle":"More about Black-Scholes","pageNumber":848,"solutions":[{"id":6357886,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"In this problem, we are asked to define option delta, vega, rho, and theta. In addition, we are also asked to define ISD.","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"## Requirement 1\n\nFirst, we will define the option delta:\n\nThe option's **delta** refers to the sensitivity of an option's value to tiny fluctuations in the underlying stock's price. It is best if the delta is negative when buying a call option since the price is higher. On the other hand, it is best if the delta is positive when buying a put option since the price is lower.","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2},{"columns":[{"text":"We will define theta:\n\nOption's **theta** is a measure of how sensitive an option's value is to a change in the time to expiry.","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":3},{"columns":[{"text":"We will define vega:\n\nOption's **vega** measures the option's price sensitivity in the standard deviation of the underlying asset's return.","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":4},{"columns":[{"text":"We will define rho:\n\nThe sensitivity of an option's value to changes in the risk-free rate is measured by **rho**.","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":5},{"columns":[{"text":"## Requirement 2\n\n\nWe will define ISD:\n\nISD stands for Implied standard deviation which estimates the future standard deviation of an asset's return derived from the Black-Scholes OPM.\n","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":6}],"rating":0,"solutionUuid":"170be5ac-0bd1-483f-8e0c-44053016a934","editorVersion":2,"answeredOn":null,"ratingCount":null,"solutionOrder":null,"totalSteps":6}],"textbook":{"authors":"Bradford D. Jordan, Randolph W. Westerfield, Stephen A. Ross","imageUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/textbook_covers/tmpm0p82b7h","imageThumbnailUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/cache/d1/d3/d1d34d106dd29dd2e71be582412ef59d.jpg","id":34320,"isbn":"9781259918957","isPremium":true,"title":"Fundamentals of Corporate Finance","edition":"12th Edition","verifiedSolutionCount":1217,"shouldBeIndexableForSeo":true,"modified":1665448474394,"active":true,"publisher":"McGraw-Hill Education","mainTextbookIsbn":null,"subjects":{"level1":["Social Science"],"level2":["Economics"],"level3":["Finance"]}},"nextExercises":[{"id":14881909,"exerciseName":"1","page":855,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"cff7d1ac-05cb-41af-b37b-99b5a48f9e1b","_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-12th-edition-9781259918957/chapter-25-concept-questions-1-cff7d1ac-05cb-41af-b37b-99b5a48f9e1b"},{"id":14881910,"exerciseName":"2","page":855,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"a576579b-e9df-4166-8f3d-ec80a2d46981","_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-12th-edition-9781259918957/chapter-25-concept-questions-2-a576579b-e9df-4166-8f3d-ec80a2d46981"}],"previousExercises":[{"id":14881901,"exerciseName":"2","page":840,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"66db2383-7ad7-4f5f-ba74-e0f2901efdae","_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-12th-editio